social_posts.post_text: “How do you know when you’re successful?” I asked Jason the other day. To be quite honest, this very moment while I was getting ready to film for McCafé was the moment I felt so successful. I looked at myself in the mirror and started thinking about my childhood, my teenage years, the awful occurrences that happened in 2020 and the doubts that my own family members would wish upon me. I started feeling powerful because I literally not only proved myself wrong and knew I was worth much more but I was proving those that doubted me wrong as well. I truly believe younger me would be SO proud to know that she’s doing fabulous and thriving in life. Success is the best revenge someone can ever have and that is why I say I’ll continue to go up 🤍

The creamer: (Cookie Butter Coffee Creamer)
•bring out a blender! 
•1 and 1/2 cup half and half (you can use any dairy substitute)
•1/2 cup creamy cookie butter
•2 teaspoons ground cinnamon
•1 teaspoon vanilla extract
•1/4 cup sweetened condensed milk.
•3 tablespoon honey or any sweetener

Blend that all together until you get a thick consistency and then store in your fridge for up to a week! 

It is so delicious! 10/10. Probably the best coffee I have ever had in such a good while!

A few weeks back, my family and I got hit hard with the flu. While we have fully recovered, I made sure to get my flu vaccine because I am definitely trying to protect not only myself but others as well. 

Did you know? When you get your flu shot, you also help protect your loved ones and people with chronic health conditions, such as heart disease and diabetes, from getting the flu. 

There were a lot of flu illnesses and hospitalizations this season, but flu activity has returned to low levels in most of the country. If flu is still spreading in your community and you haven’t been vaccinated for this season, a flu shot can still provide protection. Otherwise, remember to get vaccinated next season. It’s best to get vaccinated before flu activity starts in your community, so usually, September and October are good times to get your flu shot. 

If you don’t have a doctor whom you regularly see, flu shots are available at many locations, including local pharmacies. @Notimeforflu

For more information, head to GetMyFluShot.org and get your flu shot!

Ritmo y Color is an initiative from McDonald’s to celebrate the art and music of Latino culture. Visual artists in Latino neighborhoods around the U.S. have been invited to reimagine a McDonald’s restaurant in their community, using its outdoor facade as their canvas. In San Antonio, the selected artists are sisters Manola and Maria Ramirez!

Ritmo y Color celebrates the culture and pride of the Hispanic community. Ritmo y Color is a McDonald’s initiative that elevates the voices and stories of Latinidad through pop-up art installations and musical performances!

Their mural piece is entitled Hilos de Orientación or Threads of Guidance
This piece was inspired by the influence of their Mexican culture, traditions, and ancestors.
The shapes are inspired by the traditional folklorico dress from Jalisco, Mexico, made with ribbons that create beautiful organic shapes when the dancer swings her skirt.
The design also incorporates patterns inspired by talavera pottery, which is native to Guanajuato, where the artists’ family is from.
And the flowers are a loving tribute to their grandparents, who taught them to love nature.

Everyone is invited to come check out the beautiful new mural at McDonald’s!
You can find it at the McDonald’s at Blanco and 1604 
(address: 18146 Blanco Rd, San Antonio, TX 78232)

RECIPES: 

BREAKFAST SLIDERS: Preheat the oven to 350°F. You are going to grab your Hawaiian rolls, slice them in half, grab all the bottom of the buns and layer it onto your pan. 

Once that’s done, add your cheese on top of the bottom buns, add your scrambled eggs on top and then top it off with your cooked sausage. BACON AND EGG CUPS: Preheat the oven to 350°F and spray your muffin pan with coconut oil. 

Create a lattice for each egg cup by weaving three bacon slices together. VERY IMPORTANT: Press down into each muffin cavity so there are as little holes as possible. 

Crack an egg into each cavity.

Use a spoon to remove the bacon and egg cups from the muffin pan. Garnish with freshly chopped parsley (optional) and serve!
